HOW TO CALCULATE SPACE COMPLEXITY (UNIVERSAL METHOD)
Definition (Say this if asked)

Space complexity is the amount of extra (auxiliary) memory used by an algorithm as a function of input size.

Key word: extra
(Input storage itself is usually not counted unless explicitly asked.)

STEP-BY-STEP FRAMEWORK
STEP 1: Identify the input size variable

Array → n

Matrix → R × C

Tree → n nodes

Graph → V nodes

String → n

You must name this before giving Big-O.

STEP 2: List ALL extra memory used

Ask yourself:

Are new arrays/lists created?

Is a hash map / set used?

Is recursion used?

Is a queue or stack used?

Ignore:

Loop variables

Fixed number of integers

Temporary constants

STEP 3: Classify each memory usage
Memory Type	Space
Few variables	O(1)
Array/list of size n	O(n)
Matrix copy	O(R × C)
HashMap storing n items	O(n)
Recursion stack depth n	O(n)
Recursion stack depth log n	O(log n)
STEP 4: Take the dominant term

Same rule as time complexity.

COMMON PATTERNS (MEMORIZE THESE)
Pattern 1: No Extra Data Structures → O(1)
def max_element(arr):
    m = arr[0]
    for x in arr:
        if x > m:
            m = x
    return m


Extra memory:

One variable m

Space Complexity: O(1)

Pattern 2: New Array or List → O(n)
def reverse_copy(arr):
    res = []
    for x in arr:
        res.append(x)
    return res


Extra memory:

New array of size n

Space Complexity: O(n)

Pattern 3: HashMap / Set → O(n)
def has_duplicates(arr):
    seen = set()
    for x in arr:
        if x in seen:
            return True
        seen.add(x)
    return False


Extra memory:

Set storing up to n elements

Space Complexity: O(n)

Pattern 4: Recursion Stack (VERY IMPORTANT)
def factorial(n):
    if n == 1:
        return 1
    return n * factorial(n-1)


Extra memory:

Call stack grows to depth n

Space Complexity: O(n)

Pattern 5: Divide & Conquer Recursion
def binary_search(arr, x, l, r):
    if l > r:
        return -1
    mid = (l + r) // 2
    if arr[mid] == x:
        return mid
    elif arr[mid] < x:
        return binary_search(arr, x, mid+1, r)
    else:
        return binary_search(arr, x, l, mid-1)


Extra memory:

Call stack depth = log n

Space Complexity: O(log n)

Pattern 6: BFS / DFS
BFS (queue)
queue = []


Worst case:

All nodes in queue

Space: O(n)

DFS (recursive)

Call stack = height of tree

Tree type	Space
Balanced	O(log n)
Skewed	O(n)
Pattern 7: Grid / Matrix BFS (Rotten Oranges, Flood Fill)

Extra memory:

Queue

Visited array OR grid modification

Worst case:

All cells stored

Space Complexity: O(R × C)

Pattern 8: Sorting Space (Interview Trap)
Algorithm	Space
Merge Sort	O(n)
Quick Sort (avg)	O(log n)
Heap Sort	O(1)

Python’s sort() → O(n) auxiliary space (Timsort).

WHAT TO SAY IN INTERVIEW (STRUCTURE)

Use this format:

“The algorithm uses [data structure / recursion] which can grow up to [n / R×C / log n], so the auxiliary space complexity is O(...).”

Example:

“The BFS queue can store all grid cells in the worst case, so space complexity is O(R×C).”

COMMON MISTAKES (DO NOT DO THESE)

❌ Counting input array as space
❌ Counting loop variables
❌ Forgetting recursion stack
❌ Saying O(1) when using HashMap
❌ Saying O(n) without explaining why

QUICK DECISION TABLE
Question	Answer
New data structure grows with input?	O(n)
Only few variables?	O(1)
Recursion depth = n?	O(n)
Recursion depth = log n?	O(log n)
Grid BFS/DFS?	O(R×C)
FINAL ONE-LINE RULE (MEMORIZE)

Space complexity = max(extra memory used at any time).
